 experimentation with identity management. While recognizing that these beauty activities are potentially a form of resistance, Miller also considers the commodification of beauty, exploring how new ideals and technologies are tying consumers even more firmly to an ever-expanding beauty industry. By considering beauty in a Japanese context, Miller challenges widespread assumptions about the universality and naturalness of beauty standards.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBeauty culturezJapan. 0aBeauty, PersonalzJapan. 0aBody imagezJapan. 0aHuman bodyxSocial aspectszJapan. 0aPhilosophy, Japanese. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aaesthetic salons.  abeauty culture.  abeauty ideals.  abeauty industry.  abeauty language.  abeauty standards.  abeauty work.  abody aesthetics.  abody hair removal.  aconsumer society.  acontemporary history.  acontemporary japan.  acosmetic surgery.  acultural criticism.  adiet and health.  aelective surgery.  agender ideology.  aidentity management.  ajapanese culture.  ajapanese men.  ajapanese women.  amale beauty.  amen and women.  anonfiction.  aplastic surgery.  apopular culture.  asocial science.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024508240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093884740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938847423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520938847/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY